In article <CoM564.BAp@dcs.ed.ac.uk> pdc@dcs.ed.ac.uk (Paul Crowley) writes:
>Subject: Re: compression & security
>From: pdc@dcs.ed.ac.uk (Paul Crowley)
>Date: Thu, 21 Apr 1994 14:20:27 GMT
>Keywords: compression, Huffman, Arithmetic coding


>>(I think).  Generating plain-text that would compress to 
>>useful "chosen plain-text" in context, ( again, especially 
>>by an adaptive compressor) sounds tricky to me.

>Depends how much integrity checking your decompresser has.   Inbetween
>the header information and checksums, I think any bit vector at all is
>valid input to gzip, because it encodes the various codes it uses with
>Huffman compression, and any code in the Huffman tree is a valid one. 
>Just choose your plaintext and uncompress it!

But doesn't the meaning of the Huffman "characters" change, depending
on the characters that have gone before?  Wouldn't message headers, 
introductory text, etc.  completely change the appearance of the 
(re)compressed text?

